1204–1252","1204–Female":"1204–Overleden","1252":"1252","1350":"1350","1293":"1293","5 March 1316":"5 maart 1316","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1320":"1320","about 1224":"circa 1224","Abt 1290":"circa 1290","1317":"1317","Kelley, Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England","Kelly, Devon, England":"Kelly, Devon, England","Oar, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1224–5 March 1316":"about 1224–5 March 1316","1224–1316":"1224–1316","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1270–1320":"1270–1320","1290–1350":"1290–1350","1293–1350":"1293–1350","1204–1252":"1204–1252","1204–Female":"1204–Deceased","1252":"1252","1350":"1350","1293":"1293","5 March 1316":"5 March 1316","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1320":"1320","about 1224":"about 1224","Abt 1290":"about 1290","1317":"1317","Kelley, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England","Kelly, Devon, England":"Kelly, Devon, England","Oar, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kelly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Aileen, John Patrick, Siobhan, Liam, Brigid, Donovan, Eamon, Parnell, Aidan, Clancy.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ceallaigh</b>, or, in some areas, <b>Mac Ceallaigh</b> ‘descendant (or son) of <i>Ceallach</i>’, an ancient Irish personal name, originally a byname meaning ‘bright-headed’, later understood as ‘frequenting churches’ (Irish <i>ceall</i>). There are several early Irish saints who bore this name. <i>Kelly</i> is now the most common of all surnames in Ireland.","Scottish: habitational name from either the lands of Kelly, near Arbroath (Angus), Kellie in Carnbee (Fife), or Kelly in Methlick (Aberdeenshire). Each of these placenames is from Pictish <i>celli</i> or Gaelic <i>coille</i> ‘wood’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-in</i>. Alternatively, from the lands of Kelloe in the barony of Hume (Berwickshire), whose name is of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Kelley","meanings":["Irish (Offaly) and English: variant of   Kelly  ."]},{"name":"Kilkelly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Bridie.","Irish (Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Ceallaigh</b> ‘son of the devotee of (Saint) Ceallach’ (see   Kelly  )."]},{"name":"Killeen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donovan, Kieran, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cillín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cillín</i>’, a pet form of the personal name <i>Ceallach</i> (see   Kelly  ). The name was borne by various early Irish saints, including the leader of a 7th-century mission to Franconia and Thuringia, hence the popularity of the personal name   Kilian   in medieval central Europe."]},{"name":"Kellis","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic based on   Kelly   as a personal name. Compare   Kellison  .","Greek: descriptive nickname for a bald man, from <i>kelis</i> ‘bald’, a word of Turkish origin (from <i>kel</i> ‘bald’).","History: As a surname of Scottish origin, this has been established in NC since the 18th century."]},{"name":"Kellie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Kelly  ."]},{"name":"Kellison","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic based on   Kelly   as a personal name."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":0,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":35,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":66,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":91,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Kelly was born about 1224, in Devon, England, his father, Richard de Kelly, was 21 and his mother, Mrs. Richard de Kelly, was 22. He married Dionysia de Siccavilla about 1290. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 5 March 1316, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 93."},"et":{"about 1224–5 March 1316":"umbes 1224–5. märts 1316","1224–1316":"1224–1316","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1270–1320":"1270–1320","1290–1350":"1290–1350","1293–1350":"1293–13